    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-03-22T21:09:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-03-22T21:09:00-05:00" n="315"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d315">
                <head>315. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Thailand</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d315fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 751J.00/3–2262. Secret; Niact. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_REE1"
                            >Rice</persName>, cleared by <persName corresp="#p_KHLT1"
                            >Koren</persName>, and approved by <persName corresp="#p_JUA1"
                            >Johnson</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-03-22T21:09:00-05:00">March 22, 1962, 9:09 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1447. For <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>.</p>
                <p>In view of fact you will go Vientiane without authorization actually institute
                    military sanctions, Dept. suggests you might seek among others limited objective
                    of getting Three Princes’ negotiations going. If <persName corresp="#p_PN1"
                        >Phoumi</persName> is to put on other side onus of refusal negotiate,<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d315fn2">In telegram 1463 from Bangkok, March 23, <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> characterized this telegram as
                        “unrealistic” and stated that, “Whole world knows <persName corresp="#p_PN1"
                            >Phoumi</persName> has not at any time negotiated in good faith. No way
                        onus can be placed on other side.” (Ibid., 751J.00/3–2362)</note> or being
                    unyielding in negotiations, he must invite talks and carry them far enough
                    discover what sort cabinet distribution and arrangements for military
                    establishment he in fact could get, hopefully, such negotiations might inch two
                    sides closer to agreement, or at least by keeping talking going help hold
                    present situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Ball</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
